The biggest mistake young founders make is a variant of this: to build something you imagine people want, instead of studying them and figuring out what they actually do want. But the hack for beating this is to roll with your solipsism and make something for yourself.

This would not ordinarily work, but it happens to work with technology because the young are also the bellwethers. So if you make something you want, other people will magically turn out to want it too.

This is presumably one reason people can succeed at starting startups so young, when you have to be older to do well at most other similarly complicated things. In startups the usually fatal solipsism of the young can be turned to your advantage.

@lukepuplett Certainly since Microsoft in 1975. But I suspect it has been true for as long as people have been starting companies with a significant component of new technology. The young will have always been bellwethers in adopting new technology.

